article.description:
Nicole Brathwaite scored 26 points and
LaShondra Dixon had 25 as Hampton beat Delaware State 69-57 in the
Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference tournament championship Saturday.
article.headline: Brathwaite scores 26, Dixon 25 for 23-8 Hampton
article.linkText: Torrid one-two punch powers Hampton to title
article.story:
RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Nicole Brathwaite's propensity for foul
trouble got her a pep talk from coach Patricia Bibbs before Hampton
played Delaware State for the Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference
championship Saturday.

	   Brathwaite heard every word, then went out and scored 26 points
and had nine rebounds as top-seeded Hampton beat Delaware State 69-57 to earn its second trip to the NCAA Tournament.

	   ''It was either win the game or go home,'' Brathwaite said after
going 8-for-10 and making 10 free throws. ''I decided I wanted to
win the game.''

	   Brathwaite's production was a great companion to LaShondra
Dixon's dazzling play all over the court for the Lady Pirates
(23-8). Dixon had 25 points, eight rebounds, three steals and two
assists in 39 minutes.

	   Hampton took control with an 18-6 run that started after
Delaware State tied the game at 34-all with 17:22 remaining.
Brathwaite scored 10 points in the run and Dixon four, twice
stealing the ball at the Lady Hornets' end of the court and racing
all the way for a layup.

	   ''We didn't want the game to be within their reach,'' she said.
''We knew they would come out strong and that we had to break the
game open.''

	   The burst was capped by Brathwaite, who ended three consecutive
possessions with putbacks or layups, extending the lead to 52-40.

	   ''She was awesome in this tournament,'' Bibbs said.

	   Delaware State coach Ed Davis said his team had trouble all year
with aggressive post players, but that his program is still heading
upward.

	   ''We started 0-7,'' he said, with defeats against teams like West
Virginia and Rhode Island that helped his team come together.
''Once they learned how to play together offensively and
defensively, we kind of got focused.''

	   Besides Brathwaite, the Lady Hornets also had a hard time
stopping Dixon, who used her 5-foot-5 frame and quickness to get
key rebounds.

	   ''It's my will to want the ball,'' Dixon said. ''People don't
usually box me out because I'm small, but they pay when they look
in the box score.''

	   Delaware State (20-10), which has reached the tournament
championship in two of the past three years, still is seeking its
first NCAA bid.

	   ''As a team, we need to learn how to finish games when times get
rough,'' said Mandy Clark, who led Delaware State with 13 points
and three steals, but fouled out after 27 minutes. ''We're young.''

	   Delaware State shot 7-for-21 from 3-point range, but just 29.7
percent overall. Ashley Etheridge added 12 points and Terrelle
Waller had 10.

	   Hampton used an 11-4 run to open a 19-12 lead midway
though the first half, then went more than five minutes without a
point.

	   The Lady Hornets, sparked by six points from Etheridge, answered
with a 9-3 run to get to 22-21 and trailed just 31-28 at halftime.
